Reviews

By Anwesh Shrestha

// Book
Elon Musk
Walter Isaacson
★★★★★

Walter Isaacson is one of my favourite authors. He writes biographies — and he writes them like no one else. Raw, unfiltered, and deeply researched. His biography of Elon Musk is perhaps his most ambitious yet: a meticulous account of the life of one of the most consequential figures in the advancement of human engineering and the expansion of what we believe is possible. I finished all 600+ pages in one week — not because I had to, but because I simply could not stop. What makes Isaacson's work rare in this era is something worth noting: the subjects of his biographies have no permission to read, let alone influence, the final manuscript. In a world where narratives are constantly managed and curated, that kind of editorial independence is almost frightening in the best way. This book is essential reading.

February 2026
// Book
Atomic Habits
James Clear
★★★★★

There are books that entertain, and books that quietly rewire the way you think. Atomic Habits is the latter. James Clear does something deceptively simple — he takes the science of behaviour change and strips it down to its most honest, actionable form. The central argument is almost uncomfortably obvious once you read it: you do not rise to the level of your goals, you fall to the level of your systems. I have returned to this idea more times than I can count. What separates this book from the self-help noise is that it does not ask you to be motivated. It asks you to be architectural — to design your environment, your identity, your tiny daily repetitions. I finished it in three days and restructured my morning the day after.

// Book
Rich Dad Poor Dad
Robert T. Kiyosaki
★★★★☆

This is the book that cracked open my understanding of money. Not through spreadsheets or technical finance — but through a story, told plainly, about two very different ways of seeing the world. Kiyosaki's core distinction — between assets that put money in your pocket and liabilities that drain it — sounds simple. But the reason most people never build wealth is precisely because they have never been taught to think this way. The schools don't teach it. The parents who haven't figured it out can't teach it either. Rich Dad Poor Dad is not a blueprint. It is a lens shift. And lens shifts, once they happen, cannot be undone. I read this early, and I am glad I did.

December 2025
// Book
The 48 Laws of Power
Robert Greene
★★★★★

Robert Greene wrote this book not to make you comfortable, but to make you honest about the world as it actually operates — not as we wish it would. The 48 Laws are drawn from centuries of history: the courts of kings, the strategies of conquerors, the downfalls of the brilliant and the rises of the cunning. Some of the laws disturb you. Good. That is the point. Power is amoral, and understanding it is not the same as endorsing it. What this book gave me was not arrogance — it gave me awareness. The ability to recognise patterns in human behaviour that I had always sensed but never named. I read it slowly, one law at a time, and I will read it again.

// Book
Meditations
Marcus Aurelius
★★★★★

Marcus Aurelius was the most powerful man in the known world. He chose to spend his private hours writing reminders to himself — not speeches, not proclamations, but quiet, relentless instructions on how to be a better human being. That is what the Meditations are. They were never meant to be published. They were written for an audience of one. And that is exactly why they feel so startlingly intimate almost two thousand years later. What is not good for the swarm is not good for the bee. I have read many books on philosophy. None have made me feel the weight of my own choices quite like this one. It belongs on every shelf and, more importantly, on every bedside table.

October 2025
// Book
Bhagavad Gita
Translated by Eknath Easwaran
★★★★★

Some texts explain the world. The Bhagavad Gita asks you to examine yourself within it. Set on a battlefield, it is — on its surface — a dialogue between a warrior and his charioteer. But what unfolds is one of the most profound explorations of duty, identity, action, and detachment ever committed to language. The teaching that has stayed with me most: you have a right to perform your prescribed duty, but you are not entitled to the fruits of your action. In a world obsessed with outcomes, metrics, and results, this is almost radical. I return to this text not for answers, but for the quality of the questions it forces me to sit with.

September 2025
// Book
The Real Book of Real Estate
Robert T. Kiyosaki
★★★★☆

If Rich Dad Poor Dad is the philosophy, this is closer to the field manual. Kiyosaki assembled twenty-two real estate experts — investors, attorneys, advisors — and let each of them speak directly, in their own voice, about their specific domain. The result is a book that does not pretend to have a single answer, because real estate does not have one. What I valued most here was the honesty about risk, the specificity of the strategies, and the consistent thread running through every chapter: financial education is not optional, it is a form of self-defence. This is not light reading. It asks for your attention. But the people who take it seriously will be glad they did.
